ger and more widely spaced letters. The text closes up over lines 2 and 3, \n                                    with a more or less regular size and spacing over the rest of the stone. Interpuncts are used sparingly in the text, and their placing appears \n                                    deliberately intended to emphasise certain elements. The letters are neatly cut, with limited serifs (but sometimes substantial feet to vertical strokes), \n                                    and a tendency towards the taller narrower letters common from the second/third centuries AD onwards; this is particularly noticeable with \n                                    the letter E, which is not always easy to distinguish when corroded. Tall 'I' is employed. P is generally open.",{"_":37,"ana":38,"ref":39},"chiselled","#execution.chiselled","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1",{"dimensions":41},[42,51],{"type":43,"l":44,"from":45,"to":46,"h":47,"unit":48,"atLeast":49,"atMost":50},"letterHeight","Line 1-12","line1","line12","10-21","mm","10","21",{"type":52,"l":53,"from":45,"to":54,"unit":48},"interlinear","Not recorded","line2",{"_":56,"notBefore":57,"notAfter":58,"evidence":59},"164—166 CE, on basis of restoration of first word as Armeniacis when Aurelius and Verus both held this title",164,166,"office",[61,66],{"_":62,"type":63,"ref":64,"region":65},"Catina","ancient","http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462270","Sicilia",{"_":67,"type":68,"ref":69,"region":65},"Catania","modern","http://sws.geonames.org/2525068",[71],[72,73],37.49223,15.07041,[75,76],37.502351,15.087629,"Sicily",{"_":79,"role":80,"ref":81},"Museo Civico di Catania","museum","http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/museum/018",{"_":83,"type":84},"538","inventory",{"_":86,"mainLang":87,"languages":88},"Latin","la",[86],"175763",{"n":91,"url":92,"height":93,"width":94,"desc":95,"surfaceType":96},"screen","ISic000308_tiled.tif","2856px","4272px","I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Cu